Context:
This commit is the first full rewrite of Wrappin after deciding to abandon the old first-line-prefix toggle model. The goal was to make list handling non-lossy in the common reflow path, preserve markdown heading markers, and split semantic reflow from exact reversal of prior Wrappin output.

Rationale:
The previous implementation only derived one prefix from the first selected line and treated any multi-line selection as an unwrap operation. That broke hanging indents, merged numbered items, and stripped heading markers. The new shape is an explicit pipeline over selection data: capture range, parse rows, segment logical blocks, emit wrapped lines, and optionally track exact wrapped output with extmark-backed snapshots. Exact restore is allowed only when the selected tracked region still matches the stored wrapped text; if the user edits the region, the snapshot is invalidated and Wrappin falls back to semantic reflow.

Evidence:
- Replaced lua/scripts/wrappin.lua with a block-aware reflow engine covering plain text, repeated-prefix comments, bullets, ordered lists, and markdown headings.
- Added context inheritance so selections starting on continuation lines can pick up the surrounding list/comment schema.
- Added extmark-backed in-memory snapshots for exact restore of untouched wrapped regions.
- Expanded tests/wrappin_spec.lua to cover hanging indents, numbered-item separation, context inheritance, heading preservation, exact restore, invalidation after edits, and first-run visual mode behavior.
